[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, Lumal Labs have released their new feature modify video. Now, this is obviously a restylization of video from input video. So, video to video that is powered by their model Ray 2. If you\'ve been following the channel, you know'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that I\'m a pretty big fan of videotovideo workflow. So, I was excited to check this one out. And while I wouldn\'t qualify this as a full deep dive, this is kind of more like a first look, I did stumble my way into a few tips and tricks that might help you out'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if you decide to give it a shot. This is Ray 2\'s modify. Feel like I should do something here. Let\'s just snap out of this. So video restylizations is obviously not something brand new. In'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fact, I\'d say for many of us, our introduction to AI video came via Runway\'s Gen One, which on launch was only videotovideo. Shortly after that came the anime diff era of sort of like'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'weird, warpy, psychedelic video to video, popularized, of course, by Kyber. And more recently, of course, there\'s been a lot of AI video inpainting techniques such as Vigle, uh, popularized, of course, by the Little'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Yachty Joker viral video by AI Warper. But in terms of straight AI video restylization, it kind of has been a minute. So, it was really nice to see Luma jump feet first into the pool'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'utilizing their newest video model, Ray 2. Now, one of the things I love about video to video is how it allows you to get super creative uh with props, such as my guy here using like an ice scraper um and you know, using that as an input'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to turn it into a Viking with an axe. I do love the fact that it\'s clearly summer uh wherever he is there. uh yet he\'s still got the ice scraper probably sitting in his car. Same man, not judging. Or in this example, utilizing'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'uh like two bins, a broom, and a dustpan. Um and then somebody like writhing around underneath a blanket to turn it into a Viking ship. I mean, that\'s that\'s fun. Now, a lot of the'

[01:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'provided examples are coming from well, friend of the channel, John Finger, who I jokingly refer to as AI videos first movie star. But John\'s work always brings me a lot of joy. namely because when you when you see his'

[02:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'behindthe-scenes stuff, you\'re very quickly reconnected with that feeling of, you know, being a kid and playing with your friends. But also using video to video offers you a lot more control. Uh fingers, for example, AI video always struggles with fingers. Um when you\'re'

[02:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'utilizing a video to video process, you stand a better chance. So, since John and the gang showcase a lot of what this model can do with footage that you\'re shooting, I thought that it might be an interesting idea to uh take a different'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'approach with pre-existing assets and AI video. Now, I\'ll admit that I got off to a bit of a rocky start with the modify feature. Um, my first test was taking this V2 generated image of a a nor detective in a back alley and then we'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can bring him into Luma here. Um, that allows for a style frame. Uh, and then a couple of extra controls down here that we\'re going to go over in just a minute. So, giving it the prompt, a cyberpunk nor detective in a crime alley in a'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cyberpunk city. Uh, what I\'m going to do here is show you um where it kind of does work and then we\'re going to circle back into places that I I don\'t think it works. Um, so because we have our video here, uh, what we can do is just click'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on this option button here and then hit start frame. So, that\'s uh, you know, obviously going to download um, the first frame of your input video. Nice handy feature right there. From here, I\'m going to bring it over to'

[03:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Midjourney\'s retexture. Now, you can use any of the various like retexture, restylizers that you want to uh like flux context, whatever. I just I I happen to go over to um Midjourney for this. So, landing on this image, which'

[03:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is definitely stylistically different from our input video. And just because I still have some free trial credits over on Topaz Bloom, uh let\'s run it through a quick upscale on Bloom. Uh, apparently it did turn uh whatever like little card'

[03:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'he\'s holding here into a shot glass, but um well, he\'s had a rough day, so we\'re going to let him have it. It\'s what happens when you run things without prompts. So, bringing that image back over to Luma, we can now obviously add that in as a start frame. Uh from here,'

[03:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you do have controls uh for strength. Um this will basically allow you to choose how much influence the model is going to give uh to your video restylization. um down at the lower end, it adheres to the'

[04:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'structure and the performance details. Uh as you go up, flex would be the sort of the next level um that preserves the structure, but might take some creative liberties. Uh and then as you get into reimagine, that\'s you know, kind of'

[04:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'where it\'s going to sort of do not necessarily its own thing, but it\'s going to kind of take matters into its own hands uh to try to make the shot as best it can. Um so for now, we\'re just going to leave it in the middle here. Uh'

[04:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'roll this and see what we get. So, that initial shot comes out looking like this, which, you know, I can\'t really complain about. There\'s not a lot happening. It is sort of a boring shot. Uh, we do have the problem with the letter boxing, but that\'s, you know, that\'s pretty standard. You can always'

